properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant rain is expected. Total rainfall: 30 to 50 mm. Locally higher amounts possible. Locations: Port aux Basques and Burgeo regions. Time span: Monday through Tuesday morning. Remarks: Rain is expected to begin Monday morning and become heavy at times. Currently, the highest rainfall amounts are expected to be inland and over higher terrain, however coastal communities may still see significant amounts. The rain will taper off overnight into Tuesday. A special weather statement is already in effect for these regions for high winds associated with this same system. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow at times heavy today and tonight. Snow is forecast to begin this morning and continue into tonight. For areas near and south of Webequie, the snow is expected to transition over to a period of rain late this afternoon. After this period of rain, snow will redevelop this evening before easing overnight. Near 10 centimeters of new snowfall can be expected for areas near and south of Webequie while further north, up to 15 centimeters can be expected. Tonight, very strong northerly winds gusting up to 70 km/h will also develop, leading to reduced visibilities in blowing snow at times. This heavy snow is associated with a strengthening low pressure system that will track across northern Ontario today and tonight. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become difficult to navigate due to accumulating snow. Snowfall warnings are issued when significant snowfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A strong weather system is forecast to affect western sections of the Northwest Territories beginning Sunday afternoon and persist into early next week. Heavy snow is expected with this system, with total accumulations possibly exceeding 25 cm by Tuesday morning. The heaviest snow is predicted to fall mostly over higher terrain and over the Nahanni National Park Reserve of Canada, however accumulations are expected in communities east of these regions as well. Warnings may be issued as confidence regarding this system increases. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NTStorm.

A fast moving clipper system crossing the prairies will bring severe winds to southeastern Saskatchewan Saturday. Increasing northwesterly winds with gusts of 90 km/h or more are expected. The severe winds will continue into the afternoon hours before diminishing late in the day. ### Damage to buildings, such as to roof shingles and windows, may occur. High winds may toss loose objects or cause tree branches to break. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Heavy snow likely Saturday and Saturday night. Snow is forecast to begin Saturday morning and will then continue into Saturday night. However, for areas near and south of Attawapiskat, the snow is expected to transition over to a period of rain Saturday evening. After this period of rain, snow will redevelop Saturday night before easing Sunday morning. At this point in time, forecast guidance suggests near 10 cm of new snowfall can be expected by the time the snow comes to an end. However for areas near and south of Peawanuck, snowfall accumulations near 15 cm are possible and a Snowfall warning may be required. Also, very strong northerly winds gusting up to 70 km/h are forecast to develop Saturday night resulting in reduced visibilities in blowing snow at times. This heavy snow is associated with a strengthening low pressure system that will track across northern Ontario Saturday and Saturday night. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions are possible beginning late Sunday. A Pacific frontal system has moved into the Gulf of Alaska where it will remain nearly stationary this weekend. Further snowfall accumulations of 10 cm or more are expected today with possible rain occurring this afternoon at the pass. The main event will be late Sunday through Sunday night when snowfall amounts could reach two feet. This combined with strong north winds will create blizzard like conditions and very cold wind chills. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility in some locations. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #YTStorm.

properties.Title: Smog Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: High concentrations of fine particulates are expected and will result in poor air quality. High levels of pollutants are expected to last until Saturday morning. ### Smog especially affects asthmatic children and people with respiratory ailments or heart disease. It is therefore recommended that these individuals avoid intense physical activity outdoors until the smog warning is lifted. Additional information: To learn more about the Info-Smog program, go to Environment Canada’s website at www.canada.ca/info-smog-program. For air quality indexes in Quebec, visit the website of the Ministère de l'Environnement et de la Lutte contre les changements climatiques at www.iqa.environnement.gouv.qc.ca/contenu/index_en.asp. For the air quality index in Montréal, visit the Réseau de surveillance de la qualité de l’air de la Ville de Montréal’s website at www.rsqa.qc.ca (french only). To learn more about the effects of smog on your health in Québec, visit the Ministère de la Santé et des Services sociaux’s website at www.quebec.ca/en/health. You can also visit the Direction régionale de santé publique du CIUSSS du Centre-Sud-de-l’Île-de-Montréal at www.santemontreal.qc.ca/en/public. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant amounts of snow are expected. A Pacific frontal system has moved into the Gulf of Alaska where it will remain nearly stationary this weekend. Further snowfall accumulations of 10 to 20 cm are forecast through this evening. Gusty southwest winds will also cause local blowing snow. Warmer air associated with the system may cause a changeover to rain this afternoon before switching back to snow this evening. There will be a short break in the weather Sunday morning before a much heavier snowfall combined with strong north winds develop by the evening. This will create blizzard like conditions with very cold wind chills. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #YTStorm.

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow at times heavy today. Snow at times heavy, is expected to continue today. However, areas southeast of Sandy Lake and Summer Beaver are forecast to transition to rain this afternoon, before snow redevelops this evening. Snowfall totals in the 15 to 25 cm range can be expected by the time the snow tapers to flurries tonight or early Sunday morning. Snowfall totals are likely to be less than 15 cm in areas that transition to rain. Strong winds gusting up to 60 km/h will also accompany the snow today and tonight resulting in reduced visibilities in blowing snow at times. This snow event is associated with a strengthening low pressure system that will track eastwards across northern Ontario today and tonight. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become difficult to navigate due to accumulating snow. Snowfall warnings are issued when significant snowfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.
